Datatype In Java
 a data type defines the kind of data a variable can store and how much memory it will use.
Data types in Java are broadly classified into primitive and non-primitive (reference) types.

Java data types are divided into two main categories:
1. Primitive Data Types
These are the most basic data types in Java. There are 8 primitives:
Data Type	Size (bits)	Default Value	Example Value	Description
byte	8	0	100	Small integers (-128 to 127)
short	16	0	32000	Medium integers (-32,768 to 32,767)
int	32	0	100000	Common integer type (-2^31 to 2^31-1)
long	64	0L	10000000000L	Large integers (-2^63 to 2^63-1)
float	32	0.0f	3.14f	Single-precision decimal numbers
double	64	0.0d	3.14159	Double-precision decimal numbers
char	16	'\u0000'	'A'	Single Unicode character
boolean	1 (JVM dependent)	false	true/false	Logical values
2. Non-Primitive (Reference) Data Types
These store references (addresses) to objects, not the actual data.
Examples:
o	Strings (String name = "Java";)
o	Arrays (int[] nums = {1, 2, 3};)
o	Classes (user-defined types)
o	Interfaces
o	Enums
Example Program
public class DataTypesExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Primitive types
        byte b = 100;
        int num = 5000;
        double pi = 3.14159;
        char letter = 'J';
        Boolean  isJavaFun = true;
        // Non-primitive types
        String text = "Hello, Java!";
        int[] numbers = {1, 2, 3, 4};
        // for  Output
        System.out.println("byte: " + b);
        System.out.println("int: " + num);
        System.out.println("double: " + pi);
        System.out.println("char: " + letter);
        System.out.println("boolean: " + isJavaFun);
        System.out.println("String: " + text);
        System.out.print("Array: ");
        for (int n : numbers) {
            System.out.print(n + " ");
        }
    }
}
