Array
Collection Of same datatype ,which can hold similar type of data with continues memory
•	Fixed Size: Size must be defined at creation (in static arrays).
•	Same Data Type: All elements must be of the same type (e.g., all integers).
•	Index-Based Access: Elements are accessed using an index (starting from 0 in most languages).
•	Contiguous Memory: Elements are stored next to each other in memory.
 One-Dimensional Array
A 1D array is a list of elements stored in a single row.
Example:
public class OneDimensionalArrayExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Declare and initialize a 1D array
        int[] numbers = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};
        // Print elements of the array
        System.out.println("1D Array Elements:");
        for (int i = 0; i < numbers.length; i++) {
            System.out.println("Element at index " + i + ": " + numbers[i]);
        }
    }
}
Output:
1D Array Elements:
Element at index 0: 10
Element at index 1: 20
Element at index 2: 30
Element at index 3: 40
Element at index 4: 50
2. Two-Dimensional Array (2D)
A 2D array is like a table with rows and columns (array of arrays).
Example:
public class TwoDimensionalArrayExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Declare and initialize a 2D array
        int[][] matrix = {
            {1, 2, 3},
            {4, 5, 6},
            {7, 8, 9}
        };
        // Print elements of the 2D array
        System.out.println("2D Array Elements:");
        for (int row = 0; row < matrix.length; row++) {
            for (int col = 0; col < matrix[row].length; col++) {
                System.out.print(matrix[row][col] + " ");
            }
            System.out.println(); // Move to next row
        }
    }
}
Loop in Java
A loop is used to execute a block of code repeatedly until a certain condition is met.
Java supports three main types of loops:
1.for Loop- When the number of iterations is known. Use for loop when you know the number of iterations.
Syntax:  for(initialization; condition; update) {
    // code to execute
}
Example:
public class ForLoopExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Print numbers from 1 to 5
        for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
            System.out.println("Number: " + i);
        }
    }
}
Explanation:
•	Initialization: int i = 1 → loop starts with i = 1.
•	Condition: i <= 5 → loop runs while this is true.
•	Update: i++ → increases i by 1 after each iteration.
2.while Loop- When the number of iterations is unknown, and depends on a condition. Checks the condition before running the loop body.If the condition is false initially, the loop will not run.
Syntax:
while(condition) {
    // code to execute
}
Example:
public class WhileLoopExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int i = 1;
        while (i <= 5) {
            System.out.println("Number: " + i);
            i++;
        }
    }
}
3. do-while Loop- Similar to while, but executes.the loop body at least once, even if the condition is false initially.
Syntax:
do {
    // code to execute
} while(condition);
Example:
public class DoWhileExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int i = 1;
        do {
            System.out.println("Number: " + i);
            i++;
        } while (i <= 5);
    }
}

switch statement allows you to execute one block of code from multiple options based on a variable's value.
expression: Must be byte, short, char, int, String, or an enum.
case: Each must be a constant value.
break: Prevents fall-through to the next case.
default: Optional; runs if no case matches.
Syntax
switch (expression) {
    case value1:
        // code block
        break;
    case value2:
        // code block
        break;
    ...
    default:
        // code block if no case matches
}
Example:
import java.util.Scanner;
public class SwitchExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
        System.out.println("Enter a number (1-7) to get the day of the week:");
                // Validate input
        if (!scanner.hasNextInt()) {
            System.out.println("Invalid input! Please enter an integer between 1 and 7.");
            scanner.close();
            return;
        }
        int day = scanner.nextInt();
        // Switch statement to determine the day
        switch (day) {
            case 1:
                System.out.println("Monday");
                break;
            case 2:
                System.out.println("Tuesday");
                break;
            case 3:
                System.out.println("Wednesday");
                break;
            case 4:
                System.out.println("Thursday");
                break;
            case 5:
                System.out.println("Friday");
                break;
            case 6:
                System.out.println("Saturday");
                break;
            case 7:
                System.out.println("Sunday");
                break;
            default:
                // Executes if no case matches
                System.out.println("Invalid day number! Please enter between 1 and 7.");
        }
        scanner.close();
    }
}
